  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "/kind bug\r\n/sig node\r\n/area hw-accelerators\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nIn `/pkg/kubelet/cm/deviceplugin/manager.go` devices are allocated from a function called `allocateContainerResources`. This function inspects only container resource limits, ignoring container resource requests. This is a usability problem because it is valid to omit limits for extended resources. If limit is omitted for a device resource, then the scheduler properly places the pod with respect to available node resources. However, the device manager never dispatches to the device plugin for that resource. The result is that the user application cannot access the requested device from inside the container.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nFollowing the documented behavior of extended resources, I expected that specifying a container resource request for a device would cause the device subsystem to properly configure access for my workload.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n* Launch an alpha GKE cluster with GPU support enabled.\r\n* Attempt to run any program that accesses the GPU from a container where the resource is specified in requests but omitted from limits.\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): v1.8+\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration: device plugins enabled, devices available.\r\n",
